Hi, thanks for doing this @sholladay - is there a way to serve a directory of static files at a particular path with the correct response type set automatically?

The use case is to serve the web UI- e.g. the production build of a [create-react-app](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app) project

In Hapi, I can do this with [@hapi/inert](https://hapi.dev/family/inert/) and the `directory` handler it gives. 

```typescript
  server.route({
    method: "GET",
    path: "/app/{path*}",
    handler: {
      directory: {
        path: Path.join(__dirname, "../../client/build/"),
        listing: false,
        index: true
      }
    }
  });
```

Adds a `DOCS/Examples` page to the storybook where the examples work against live data.

#### Why

- Storybook works with mock data. But when developing/fixing Gearbox components, we often need to work with live data. Currently, Gearbox developers temporarily modify the stories to work against a live `CogniteClient` instance when needed. These modifications are not committed. This PR improves on this by providing the scaffolding to experiment/test with live data.
- Storybook examples are very basic- each story's intent is to illustrate one aspect of a component.  On the other hand, the intent of one of these examples is to illustrate more concrete use cases- often involving multiple interacting components.

#### An Example

The `src/examples/Sandbox`:

```jsx
import React, { useContext } from 'react';
import { AssetTree } from '../components/AssetTree';
import { ClientSDKProvider } from '../components/ClientSDKProvider';
import { AppContext } from './app/App';

export Sandbox = () => {
  const ctx = useContext(AppContext);

  return (
    <ClientSDKProvider client={ctx!.client!}>
      <AssetTree />
    </ClientSDKProvider>
  );
};
```

#### The AppContext

The `AppContext` is in the shape of:

```typescript
{
  client: CogniteClient | null;
  project: string;
  loggedIn: boolean;
  onLogin: (arg0: LoginFormParams) => void;
  onLogout: () => void;
}
```

The stories in `src/examples/Examples.story.mdx` are all decorated with the `App` component which provides the `AppContext` to its descendants.

```jsx
<Meta title="Docs/Examples" decorators={[storyFn => <App>{storyFn()}</App>]} />
```

The `AppContext` is resoponsible for managing the "Application aspects" on behalf of all the examples; such as login-in to the CDF using a `CogniteClient` instance.

The `Menu` component uses the `AppContext` to provide the user info and sign-out button.

#### Authentication

When mounted, the `App` component checks if user credentials (`project` and `token`) are stored in the local storage and initialises a `CogniteClient` instance and renders its children. If the credentials are not saved, it displays the login screen. This works very nicely with Storybook's hot reloading.

